First week on this plan and honestly it's been pretty solid! The shakshouka breakfast is way better than I expected - never really cooked with tomato sauce for breakfast before but it's filling and tasty. The kabsa is my favorite meal, reminds me of home cooking. I struggled a bit with the jareesh at first since I'm not the best cook, but by day 4 I got the hang of it. The workouts are tough though - those advanced routines are no joke for someone at my level. My legs were absolutely destroyed after the first leg day, could barely walk the next day. Had to skip one upper body session on Thursday because I was too sore and didn't sleep well Wednesday night. The labneh and dates combo is surprisingly good for a snack, keeps me going between meals. I'm eating most of what's planned but sometimes can't finish all the jareesh in meal 4, probably hitting around 2600 kcal most days instead of the full 2800. Feeling stronger already though, and the soreness is getting a bit better. Sleep has been okay, averaging around my usual 7 hours but had a couple nights where I only got 6 because of work stress.

Week 2 of my muscle gain journey (W47) was definitely challenging but I can see small improvements from last week. Started at 65.9kg and I'm happy to report I'm seeing some gains!

Monday kicked off with W25 (full body strength) - the compound movements are still tough but I'm getting better at form. Hit about 85% of my calorie target (2070 kcal) because I underestimated portion sizes for my chicken and rice meal. Still learning to eyeball portions as a beginner cook.

Tuesday was a rest day and I actually nailed my nutrition - 2450 kcal. Meal prepped some basic chicken breasts and rice which saved me time. Sleep was rough though, only got 6.5 hours due to work stress.

Wednesday's W21 workout (upper body focus) felt brutal on my chest and shoulders. Definitely experienced DOMS from Monday still lingering. Managed about 2380 kcal. My budget of 40 SAR/day is workable but I'm buying in bulk - eggs, chicken, rice, and budget protein powder are my staples.

Thursday I was supposed to rest but felt sluggish all day. Only hit 2200 kcal because I skipped my evening snack - just wasn't hungry and sleep deprivation caught up with me (6.2 hours). This is where my 75% adherence shows.

Friday's W25 session was better than Monday! I could feel slight strength improvements, especially on squats. Got 2500 kcal in, slightly over target but needed it for recovery. Sleep improved to 7.1 hours.

Saturday's W21 workout almost didn't happen - I was tempted to skip due to fatigue but pushed through at 70% intensity. Hit 2380 kcal. My cooking is definitely improving; made a decent stir-fry without burning anything!

Sunday rest day, focused on recovery. Ate 2420 kcal, meal prepped for next week, and got 7.5 hours of sleep finally.

Overall: The workouts are intense for my beginner level - some exercises I had to reduce weight or modify. DOMS in legs and chest was real, especially days 2-4. My adherence was about 75% as expected - hit 3.5 out of 4 workouts at full intensity, and nutrition was 85-95% of target most days. Budget held up fine with smart shopping. The 6.9 hour average sleep is my biggest barrier; I need to prioritize rest more for muscle recovery.

Physically, I feel slightly fuller in my chest and arms, though it might be pump and water retention. Energy levels varied - high after good sleep, dragging after poor sleep. No injuries, just normal beginner soreness. Looking forward to week 3 with better sleep habits!

Week 48 is complete! Overall, I'd say this was a solid week with some real-world challenges that tested my commitment. Started Monday strong with W25 (Upper Body Push) - the bench press variations and overhead work really challenged me, especially since I'm still at beginner level. Tuesday's W21 (Lower Body Pull) had me feeling those deadlifts and hamstring curls for days afterward. The DOMS was real, but I managed it with extra stretching and made sure to hit my protein targets.

Mid-week got tricky. Wednesday I had a late work commitment that pushed my sleep to only 6 hours, which affected my Thursday W25 session - I completed it but had to drop the weight on my last few sets. Friday's W21 went better after catching up on sleep. The weekend was crucial for recovery.

Nutrition-wise, I'm getting better at meal prep. Bulk-bought chicken breast, rice, and oats at the start of the week which kept me under budget. My cooking is improving - only burned one batch of rice this week (progress!). I averaged around 2380 kcal daily, slightly under my 2430 target, mainly because Thursday I was too tired to eat my evening snack. Protein intake was consistent at ~150g/day thanks to my whey protein stash.

Sleep averaged 6.7 hours this week - a bit below my usual 6.84. Tuesday and Wednesday nights were rough due to work stress and some lingering muscle soreness. I'm learning that recovery is just as important as the workouts themselves.

Missed zero workouts completely, which I'm proud of, though that Thursday session was definitely at 80% intensity. My 75% adherence propensity was tested but I pushed through. Budget held at around 38 SAR/day - the bulk buying strategy is working well.

Physically, I feel slightly fuller in my chest and shoulders, and my lifts are incrementally improving. The scale shows a small uptick which is expected with muscle gain goals. Energy levels are decent despite the sleep debt. Looking forward to next week and maintaining this momentum!

Week 49 complete! Started strong with good energy on Days 1-2, hitting both W25 workouts at full intensity. The higher calorie target (2508 kcal) was challenging to meet consistently on my 40 SAR budget, but I managed by buying bulk rice, chicken thighs, and eggs. Day 3's W25 session felt harder - probably the accumulated fatigue from two heavy sessions plus only 6.5 hours sleep. Had to reduce weight by about 10% on the last two compound movements.

Day 4's W21 workout went better than expected despite lingering soreness. My beginner cooking skills are improving - meal prepping Sunday helped a lot. Made a big batch of chicken and rice that lasted three days. Days 5-7 were rest days which I used to catch up on sleep (averaged 7.2 hours those nights vs 6.3 on training days).

Budget-wise, I spent 38.5 SAR/day average. Skipped some of the more expensive protein sources and relied heavily on eggs and canned tuna. Fiber intake was lower than target most days (averaged 21g vs 25g target). Noticed I'm getting hungrier between meals now - probably the muscle-building process kicking in.

This week was a real learning experience for me! I'm still pretty new to structured fitness and meal planning, so there were definitely some ups and downs. 

On the diet side, I managed to stick to the plan about 60-65% of the time. The meals were actually pretty filling - maybe too filling sometimes! I really loved the chicken kabsa and jarish with lamb - those were my absolute favorites and I looked forward to those days. The flavors were amazing and they kept me satisfied for hours. However, I did skip my afternoon snacks on Tuesday and Friday because I was just so full from lunch, and honestly, I was running a bit late on those days too. On Wednesday, I ate slightly smaller portions at dinner because I felt a bit bloated from the day before. The budget of 60 SAR per day was mostly manageable, though I had to be careful with my grocery shopping and stick to local markets.

For workouts, I completed all 4 sessions as planned (W25 on Monday and Wednesday, W21 on Tuesday and Thursday), which I'm really proud of! But I have to be honest - I had to modify almost everything to beginner level. The advanced exercises were just too complex for me right now. I used lighter weights than recommended, maybe 40-50% of what was suggested, and I took longer rest periods between sets. Some of the compound movements were confusing at first, and I had to watch tutorial videos on my phone between sets. My form probably wasn't perfect, but I tried my best. By Thursday, I was feeling pretty sore, especially in my legs and shoulders.

Sleep was decent - I averaged about 7.3 hours per night, which is close to my usual 7.4. I did have one rough night on Wednesday when I stayed up later than planned scrolling through social media (oops!). 

Overall, I'm feeling optimistic but realistic. I know muscle gain takes time, especially for someone like me who's just starting out. I felt a tiny bit stronger by the end of the week, and my clothes fit about the same. The scale went up very slightly, which I'm hoping is some water retention and maybe a tiny bit of muscle? I'm trying not to obsess over the numbers too much. The biggest challenge was definitely the workout complexity - I need to maybe find some beginner-specific modifications or stick with simpler programs until I build more confidence and strength. But I'm committed to keeping at it!

Week 2 of my muscle gain journey is complete! I went into this week feeling more confident after surviving Week 1's soreness, though my muscles were still a bit tender at the start. 

Diet-wise, I managed better this week - hit about 68% adherence compared to last week's 63%. I meal prepped chicken kabsa on Sunday which saved me so much time and money. Shopping at the local market early helped me stay within my 60 SAR daily budget. I did skip my evening snack on Tuesday and Thursday because I was genuinely too full after dinner, and on Saturday I had a family gathering where I ate what was served instead of my planned meals. The jarish with lamb continues to be my favorite - it's filling and I can feel it helping with recovery.

Workouts were challenging but I'm seeing small improvements! Completed all 4 sessions (W25 on Monday and Thursday, W21 on Tuesday and Friday). I'm still using modified weights - managed to increase by about 5-10% on some exercises compared to last week, so now I'm at roughly 45-55% of recommended weights. The push-ups are getting slightly easier, though I'm still doing them on my knees. The DOMS wasn't as brutal this week - only moderate soreness on Wednesday and Saturday, which I'm taking as a good sign that my body is adapting.

Sleep averaged around 7.2 hours - pretty consistent with my usual pattern. A couple nights I stayed up later than planned scrolling through workout form videos on YouTube, which I think actually helped me feel more confident in the gym.

Biggest win: I could actually feel my arms and shoulders engaging during the exercises this week, whereas last week everything just felt awkward and difficult. My form is improving and I'm starting to understand the mind-muscle connection people talk about. Still struggling with some of the more complex movements, but I'm not as intimidated anymore.

Challenges remain around exercise complexity - I spent extra time watching tutorials before each session. Also, the gym can be crowded after work, which sometimes means waiting for equipment or feeling self-conscious. But I'm pushing through!

Overall feeling: Cautiously optimistic. I can see this is going to be a long journey, but these small improvements are motivating. My clothes fit the same, but I swear my shoulders look slightly different in the mirror. Might be wishful thinking, but I'll take it!

Week 3 felt like a real turning point! I'm genuinely starting to feel stronger and more confident in the gym. Week 5 is complete and I'm honestly amazed at how this has become part of my routine now. Started the week at 50.6kg and ended at 51.1kg - that half-kilo gain feels earned and intentional, not just random fluctuation. All 4 workouts completed again, making this my second consecutive perfect week. The W25 full-body sessions on Monday and Friday felt powerful - I'm now using 65% of recommended weights on most compound movements, up from 60% last week. The W21 upper body days (Wednesday and Saturday) showed real progress too - push-ups are getting smoother and I managed 8 consecutive proper-form reps before needing a knee modification.

Diet adherence averaged around 72% this week, which is slightly down from last week's 73-75%, but honestly still feels sustainable. I had two challenging days: Tuesday when I stayed late at the library studying and grabbed a shawarma wrap that pushed me 250 kcal over target, and Thursday when my roommate made kunafa and I couldn't resist (worth it, but added about 400 kcal). I compensated both times by adjusting the following day's portions. My Sunday meal prep included a new experiment - I marinated chicken thighs in yogurt and za'atar overnight, then grilled them. Game changer for flavor! Made the whole week's lunches more exciting.

Protein intake stayed strong at 118-128g daily range. I'm getting better at hitting my targets even on busier days. My go-to quick protein sources are now automatic: Greek yogurt with honey in the morning, chicken or eggs at lunch, and usually fish or more chicken at dinner. I've also discovered that adding a scoop of protein powder to my morning oats makes a huge difference in keeping me full until lunch.

The visible changes are becoming undeniable. My roommate commented again this week that my shoulders look 'more athletic' and I can see definition in my deltoids that wasn't there a month ago. The diet plan is solid when I can stick to it, but 25 SAR/day is tight—had to swap some proteins for cheaper options mid-week (more eggs, less chicken). Sleep stayed around 6.5 hours most nights; I know I need more but work and life just don't allow it right now. Energy-wise, I'm functional but not thriving—afternoon slumps are real. I can see a tiny bit more definition in my abs when I flex, which is motivating. Sodium went over target 3 days this week (fast food culprits). Hydration was better—kept a water bottle with me. Wednesday's full body (W29) was rougher—legs were still sore and I cut two sets short because I had to rush to work. Friday's workout (W21) was probably my best, around 65% intensity, form felt cleaner on squats than it has in weeks.

Ended up doing two fast food runs (shawarma Wednesday night, cheap burger Friday lunch) because I just didn't have time or ingredients to cook. Skipped breakfast 3 times this week—just couldn't wake up early enough with the 6-6.5 hours of sleep I'm getting. Afternoon crashes were brutal, especially Tuesday and Thursday. I'd be at my desk just zoning out around 3pm.

Protein took a hit—swapped chicken for eggs more than I wanted to because eggs are 1/3 the price. Made a lot of 3-egg omelets with whatever veggies I had. Rice and lentils became my carb staples again. Tried to add some variety with a tomato-based rice dish I saw online, turned out okay. Sodium was definitely high—I can feel it, woke up bloated at least 3 mornings. Probably hit 2400-2600mg on those fast food days.

Body-wise, I'm seeing continued progress in the mirror. Midsection is definitely leaner, can see more ab definition when I flex in good lighting. Arms look a bit fuller, especially biceps. Scale dropped a bit which is encouraging. Energy levels are my biggest enemy right now—the sleep deficit is catching up. I know 6.5 hours isn't enough but between work and trying to fit in workouts and meal prep, something's gotta give.

Strength gains are small but there—added 2.5kg to my dumbbell press on Monday, held it for all sets. Push-ups felt easier on Friday. Still can't do a proper pull-up but negatives are getting more controlled. No injuries, just normal muscle soreness that faded by mid-week. DOMS from Monday's workout was manageable, way better than early December.

Barriers remain the same: 25 SAR daily budget is tight, especially for quality protein. Sleep is non-negotiable bad right now due to work schedule. Cooking skill is improving but I'm still limited to maybe 5-6 reliable dishes. Time is always squeezed. Next week I need to prioritize meal prep earlier and maybe find cheaper protein sources—thinking canned tuna or more legumes. Overall, not perfect, but I'm still moving forward. The consistency on workouts feels good even when diet isn't ideal.

Cooking skill is improving slowly. I made a decent lentil and vegetable soup on Sunday that'll carry me into next week. Learning to season chicken thighs properly so they're not bland. Still a beginner but gaining confidence.

Overall, I'm seeing physical progress which keeps me motivated, but the lifestyle factors (sleep, budget, time) are constant friction. Day 4 (Thursday): Another rest day, but felt guilty about skipping Wednesday. Tried to eat cleaner - oatmeal, canned tuna, vegetables. Got about 1650 kcal. Sleep improved to 6.5 hours.

Day 5 (Friday): Attempted W25 again. This time I modified heavily - did bodyweight squats instead of barbell, skipped deadlifts entirely, did some push-ups and planks. Maybe 30 minutes total, very light intensity. Felt better mentally for doing SOMETHING. Food was decent: 2000 kcal, mostly whole foods.

Day 6 (Saturday): Should have done W21 but went out with friends instead. Ended up at a fast-food place (off-plan meal #2) - burger and fries. Probably consumed 2400 kcal for the day. Only got 5 hours of sleep due to staying out late.

Day 7 (Sunday): Completely skipped planned workout. Felt bloated and tired from Saturday. Did some meal prep for next week but energy was low. Ate around 1700 kcal - chicken, rice, some vegetables.

The W25/W21 programming continues to be too advanced for my current fitness level. I can't complete the prescribed sets and reps, and the complexity of the movements (especially with barbell work) is intimidating when I'm alone at home with no spotter or proper form check. The 2730 kcal target also feels impossible to hit consistently on my 30 SAR/day budget while eating clean - I'm constantly choosing between hitting calories or hitting protein, and usually falling short on both.

My motivation is at an all-time low. I spent about 245 SAR this week (15 SAR over budget) due to the two off-plan meals and some extra protein sources I tried to buy. The scale barely moved, and I don't see any visible changes. I'm starting to wonder if this approach is right for me, or if I need something more sustainable and beginner-appropriate.

Physically, I'm less sore than last week, but that's mainly because I barely worked out. My energy levels are poor - the 6 hours of sleep isn't cutting it, especially with work demands. I feel like I'm in a cycle of planning to work out, failing to execute, feeling guilty, eating poorly to cope, then repeating.

Positives: I did manage 1.5 workouts (better than 0), and I'm learning what doesn't work for me. I also realize I need to either find a simpler program or get some in-person coaching to learn proper form.

Week 3 has been the hardest yet. I started Monday with some hope after the weekend, but reality hit fast. The 2806 kcal target feels impossible when I'm this exhausted and my budget is already stretched. I managed to hit the gym twice this week, but both sessions were heavily modified versions of W25 - I just can't do the barbell work safely when I'm running on 5-6 hours of sleep and minimal food. 

The diet adherence crashed to around 40% this week. I averaged maybe 1720 kcal per day, which is over 1000 kcal below target. I had three off-plan meals (Tuesday night I grabbed a cheap burger because I was too tired to cook, Thursday was shawarma again, and Sunday I just ate whatever was easy). My protein is probably around 85g daily - I know it should be 210g but chicken breast and eggs add up fast on 30 SAR/day, especially when I need to buy other food too.

Workouts were 1.5 out of 4 completed. Monday I did about 60% of W25 Day 1 - some dumbbell work and bodyweight stuff, skipped the barbell movements entirely. Wednesday I was supposed to do W21 but I was so drained I just walked on the treadmill for 20 minutes. Friday I attempted W25 Day 3 and got through maybe half before my energy completely tanked. Sunday's W21 session didn't happen - I slept through my alarm.

Sleep averaged 5.8 hours this week (range: 5-6.5 hours). I'm in a vicious cycle: can't sleep well because I'm stressed about not hitting targets, then can't hit targets because I'm exhausted. The guilt is eating me alive. I spent about 248 SAR this week, which is 38 SAR over budget for the week. I had to buy some basics mid-week and prices are just higher than I budgeted for.

The psychological weight is the worst part. Every skipped workout, every meal that doesn't hit macros, every night of bad sleep - it all piles up. I feel like I'm failing at something that should be straightforward. The W25/W21 programming still feels completely wrong for where I'm at. I need something I can actually complete, not something that makes me feel inadequate every single session.

I'm starting to think I need to either find a way to get professional help (trainer, nutritionist, something) or completely redesign this myself with much lower targets. The current approach isn't sustainable and I can feel myself spiraling.

Week 4 (2025-W51) was the breaking point I desperately needed, though not in the way I'd hoped. Coming off three weeks of spiraling failure, I knew something had to change. The pattern was clear: 5.8 hours of sleep, chronic stress, impossible workouts (W25/W21), and a massive caloric deficit leaving me exhausted and guilty.

Monday started with good intentions. I woke up at 6:15am after only 5.5 hours of sleep, groggy and unmotivated. I attempted W25 Day 1 but my body just... gave up. I completed maybe 35% - some warm-up movements, two sets of the first exercise, then I sat on the bench staring at my phone for 10 minutes before leaving. The defeat was crushing. Diet-wise, I managed breakfast (eggs, toast) and a protein shake, but lunch was a cheap shawarma again (95 SAR overspent already in my head from last week). Dinner was skipped. Total: ~1450 kcal, maybe 70g protein.

Tuesday I didn't even attempt the gym. Work stress hit hard, and I slept terribly (5 hours). I grabbed convenience foods: packaged sandwiches, chips, an energy drink to stay awake. Around 1600 kcal, mostly carbs and fat. I felt like a failure but was too exhausted to care.

Wednesday was supposed to be W25 Day 2. I went to the gym at 7pm, changed into my workout clothes, and just... walked on the treadmill for 25 minutes at a slow pace while watching YouTube. It was all I could manage. I told myself 'something is better than nothing' but felt pathetic. Diet was slightly better: chicken and rice from a budget place (55 SAR), protein shake, some fruit. Maybe 1850 kcal, 95g protein.

Thursday was my turning point, but not a good one. I woke up after 6.5 hours of sleep (best of the week) and realized I was dizzy when standing. I've been under-eating for weeks, barely sleeping, and pushing a body that's screaming for rest. I made a decision: I'm not going to the gym today, and I'm going to actually eat. I had a proper breakfast, a full lunch with colleagues (which broke my budget further - 45 SAR), and a decent dinner. Total: ~2200 kcal. No workout. I felt guilty but also... relieved?

Friday I attempted W25 Day 3, managing about 45% completion. My strength felt slightly better after actually eating Thursday, but the programming is still far beyond my current capacity. The workout calls for complex movements and rep schemes I can't execute with proper form. I'm not recovering between sessions, and my sleep debt is astronomical. Diet: 1750 kcal, 80g protein. Budget meal prep is falling apart.

Saturday (W21 scheduled) I completely skipped. I slept until 10am (7 hours! - my body finally crashed), and spent the day doing laundry, meal prep attempts, and just... existing. I made simple chicken, rice, and vegetables for the next few days. Ate about 1900 kcal. No guilt today, just acceptance that I can't continue like this.

Sunday I did a modified workout - completely ignored the W21 programming and just did basic movements I actually know: bodyweight squats, push-ups (on knees), dumbbell rows, and 20 minutes of walking. It felt... good? Like I was actually exercising instead of failing at exercise. Total time: 40 minutes. Diet: 1850 kcal from my meal prep.

Week totals: 1.75/4 workouts completed (being generous with my definitions), average 1800 kcal/day (1035 kcal deficit from target), estimated 82g protein/day (129g short), 6.0 hours sleep average (up from 5.8 - small win), and budget disaster: ~285 SAR spent vs 210 SAR target (75 SAR overage).

Physically, I'm lighter but I look worse. My face is gaunt, my lifts have stalled or regressed, and I'm constantly cold. The scale dropped but I'm losing muscle along with fat. My clothes fit looser but I don't look 'fit' - I look depleted. Energy levels are rock bottom except for Thursday when I actually ate properly.

Mentally, I'm in crisis. The guilt-stress-insomnia cycle is real and vicious. Every missed workout adds to my anxiety, which ruins my sleep, which tanks my energy, which causes me to miss more workouts. I'm stuck in a pattern I can't break alone. The W25/W21 programming is demoralizing - it's designed for someone with a training base, proper recovery, and adequate nutrition. I have none of these.

The brutal truth: I need help. I need a program designed for actual beginners with recovery constraints. I need to eat at a smaller deficit (maybe 500 kcal, not 1000+). I need to prioritize sleep over early morning workouts. I need to accept that 4 days/week might be too much right now. And I need to stop the shame spiral that's making everything worse.

I'm not quitting, but I can't continue this path. Week 4 was a 40% adherence week overall, same as Week 3, but it felt different - less like failure, more like a wake-up call. Something has to change, and it has to start with realistic expectations and self-compassion I haven't shown myself.

Week 5 became a turning point, but not in the way I hoped. After last week's crisis, I tried telling myself Monday would be different - I'd follow the plan, hit my calories, get proper sleep. Reality hit hard.

Monday started with good intentions. Woke up exhausted after 5.5 hours sleep, dragged myself to W25 Day 1. Got through the warm-up and first exercise, then just... stopped. Standing there in the gym, I felt this wave of complete emptiness. Not even guilt anymore, just hollow. Completed maybe 30% before walking out. Grabbed a shawarma on the way home (190 SAR left for the week already). Ate 1650 kcal total - my stomach's shrunk so much that normal portions feel huge.

Tuesday I made a decision: I'm taking a real break. Not 'skipping' - actively choosing rest. Slept 7 hours for the first time in weeks. Didn't track food, just ate when hungry. Maybe 1900 kcal? Felt guilty but also... relieved? My body needed this.

Wednesday, tried W21. The 'easier' program felt impossible. My strength is just gone. Exercises I could do a month ago - can't hit the reps. Had to modify everything, use lighter weights, rest longer. Finished about 50% of prescribed work. The guy next to me was warming up with my working weight. That stung. Budget crisis deepened - bought pre-made protein box (expensive but I couldn't face cooking). Down to 95 SAR with 4 days left.

Thursday and Friday blurred together. Skipped both workouts. Thursday I slept 6.5 hours, Friday only 5. The guilt-insomnia cycle is back but different - now it's mixed with this resignation. I know I'm failing but I'm too tired to care properly. Ate around 1750-1800 kcal both days, mostly cheap carbs and whatever protein I could afford. Bought bulk eggs and rice. Budget completely blown - had to dip into next week's money.

Saturday I looked in the mirror and barely recognized myself. I'm gaunt. My face is hollow, collarbones jutting out, but I still have this belly fat that won't budge. The worst kind of skinny-fat. I'm cold constantly - wearing two layers indoors. Did a 30-minute walk just to move, but it felt like I was dragging dead weight.

Sunday, rock bottom. Slept 5 hours, woke up with a pounding headache. Skipped the workout entirely. Sat down and actually calculated: I've been in a 1000+ calorie deficit for a month while trying to do intermediate programming on beginner recovery capacity with chronic sleep deprivation. No wonder I'm falling apart.

The scale shows 88.1 kg - I've lost 2.2 kg this week alone. But my clothes fit weird - loose in the arms and chest, tight around the middle. I'm losing muscle faster than fat. My lifts have regressed to below where I started. I'm weaker, more tired, and honestly scared about what I'm doing to myself.

I completed 1.5 out of 4 planned workouts (38% adherence). Diet averaged maybe 1775 kcal vs 2738 target - a 963 kcal daily deficit that's clearly unsustainable. Sleep averaged 5.9 hours. Budget disaster: spent approximately 340 SAR on 210 SAR budget (130 SAR overage, had to borrow from next week).

The notes say 'urgent intervention needed' and they're right. I can't keep doing this. I need to either get actual help - a real coach, a nutritionist, maybe even therapy for the stress-guilt cycle - or I need to completely redesign this myself. Smaller deficit, way easier workouts, sleep as priority #1. Maybe even take a full week off to recover.

I'm at a crossroads. Part of me wants to quit entirely. Another part knows I'll hate myself if I do. But continuing like this isn't working either - it's just slow-motion self-destruction. I've lost weight but I look and feel worse than when I started. That's not progress, that's just... damage.

Next week, something has to fundamentally change. I can't willpower my way through this anymore.

Week 6 was supposed to be different. I told myself after last week's collapse that I'd get it together, but honestly? It was more of the same downward slide, just with slightly different flavors of failure.

Monday started with W25 Day 1 again - my third attempt at this workout in two weeks. I managed about 45% of it this time, which felt like a victory compared to last week's 30% emotional shutdown, but it's still pathetic. My arms were shaking during the warm-up push-ups. The barbell squats that used to feel manageable at 40kg? I'm down to 30kg and even that feels heavy. I can see it in the mirror at the gym - my shoulders look narrower, my chest is flat, but I've still got this soft layer around my midsection that won't budge. I'm literally getting smaller and fatter at the same time.

Tuesday I actually showed up for W21, which surprised me. Got through maybe 55% before my lower back started screaming during deadlifts. I had to drop the weight twice mid-set. The guy next to me was warming up with what I was struggling to lift. That comparison trap is poisonous, I know, but it's hard not to notice.

Wednesday was supposed to be W25 Day 3, but I woke up so exhausted I couldn't even think about it. Skipped. Thursday I dragged myself in for W21 again and managed about 40%. My form is falling apart - I can feel it. Everything feels loose and uncoordinated. I'm pretty sure I'm going to hurt myself if I keep pushing like this.

Friday through Sunday: nothing. Complete shutdown. I didn't even do a walk. Just stayed in my room mostly, scrolling through my phone, feeling the hours drain away.

The diet situation is beyond crisis now - it's just reality. I'm eating whatever I can afford, which means a lot of white rice, cheap bread, and the occasional egg or chicken when I can stretch the budget. I estimated maybe 1,650 calories per day this week, and protein was probably around 70g on good days. I'm hungry all the time, but I'm also too tired to care about eating properly. The budget is completely blown - I'm at about 380 SAR spent over the past two weeks when I should be at 420 SAR total. I've been borrowing from my rent money. That's a new low.

Sleep is still terrible. 5.7 hours average this week. I lie awake thinking about how badly I'm failing, then I'm too tired to function the next day, then I feel guilty about wasting the day, then I can't sleep again. Perfect cycle.

I weighed myself today and I'm down another 1.9kg. That's 4.1kg in two weeks. I know that's not healthy. I can see it - my face looks gaunt, my collarbones are prominent, but my stomach still pouches out when I sit down. I'm cold constantly. My hands shake sometimes. This morning I felt dizzy standing up from bed.

The scary part? I'm starting to feel numb about it. Last week I was panicking. This week I'm just... resigned? Like I'm watching myself fail from outside my body. I know I need help. I know this is unsustainable. I know I'm probably doing long-term damage. But the gap between knowing and doing feels impossibly wide right now.

I did have one moment of clarity on Saturday night. I was lying in bed, too wired to sleep despite being exhausted, and I realized: I'm not on a fitness journey anymore. I'm just in a slow-motion health crisis. The program isn't the problem - I am. Or rather, the way I'm trying to do this is fundamentally broken.

I need to eat more. I need to sleep more. I need to do less. Those three things are obvious. But actually implementing them feels like trying to turn around an aircraft carrier with a paddle. Everything is connected - the budget affects the food, the food affects the energy, the energy affects the sleep, the sleep affects the workouts, the failed workouts affect my mental state, and around and around.

I think I'm scared to actually change because changing means admitting I've been doing this wrong for six weeks. It means letting go of the aggressive deficit, the ambitious workout schedule, the idea that I can willpower my way through this. It means accepting that I'm more broken down than I thought.

But here's the thing: I'm still writing this entry. I'm still tracking. Some tiny part of me hasn't given up completely. I just don't know if that's resilience or stubbornness at this point.

Week 7 complete. I need to be honest - this was supposed to be a recovery week where I stopped training and ate more, but I couldn't fully commit to either. The dissociation I mentioned last week got worse. I'd stare at my meal prep notes for 20 minutes without moving, or stand in front of the gym deciding whether to go in. I managed 2 workouts instead of the prescribed 4, both at maybe 50% effort. The tremors in my hands are constant now - I noticed while trying to load plates that my grip feels weak and shaky. Diet improved slightly because I forced myself to buy rotisserie chicken twice (60 SAR total, way over budget but I was desperate for easy protein). Still only hitting maybe 1,850 kcal/day instead of the 2,626 target. Sleep got marginally better at 6.1 hours because I was too exhausted to stay awake with guilt. The scary part: I've stopped feeling hungry. My body just... gave up asking. I lost another 1.1kg this week, and I can see my shoulder bones clearly now. A coworker asked if I was sick. I lied and said I had the flu. The numbness is almost comfortable compared to the panic from weeks ago, which I know is a bad sign. I keep thinking I should ask for help but then I don't know what I'd even say. 'I'm slowly destroying myself following a fitness plan?' It sounds ridiculous. But I also know this can't continue. Maybe next week.

Week 8 became the breaking point I'd been circling for months. Monday started with me staring at the meal plan - 2,539 kcal, 190g protein - numbers that felt like they belonged to someone else's life. The tremors in my hands made it hard to hold my phone steady while logging. I knew I was in trouble, but the 'comfortable numbness' had become a prison.

The first two days, I barely ate. Maybe 1,200 kcal each day. Rotisserie chicken again because I couldn't think of anything else, but even that tasted like cardboard. My body had stopped sending hunger signals entirely. I'd sit with food in front of me and just... stare. The dissociation was complete - like watching someone else fail from behind glass.

Wednesday morning I couldn't get out of bed for the workout. Not 'didn't want to' - physically couldn't. My legs wouldn't respond properly. I called in sick to work for the first time, told them it was a stomach bug. Spent the day sleeping in 90-minute chunks, waking up disoriented each time. The cold sensitivity was so bad I wore two hoodies indoors with the heat on.

Thursday something shifted. Maybe it was seeing 82.3kg on the scale (I'd lost another 2.8kg in 4 days), or the way my coworker asked if I was okay with genuine concern in his eyes, or just animal survival instinct kicking in. I used my lunch break to search 'signs of starvation' and the list read like my diary: rapid weight loss, muscle wasting, tremors, cold intolerance, fatigue, loss of appetite, difficulty concentrating. The phrase 'refeeding syndrome' scared me enough to finally text my older brother.

He video-called immediately. Seeing his face - the shock in his expression when he saw me - broke through the fog. He made me promise to see a doctor and sent me 500 SAR 'no arguments, not a loan.' That money felt like a lifeline and a failure simultaneously.

Friday I managed a doctor's appointment (280 SAR, covered by brother's money). The physician was direct: 'You're in acute malnutrition. BMI approaching underweight, showing signs of muscle catabolism, possible electrolyte imbalances. We need bloodwork immediately.' He ordered comprehensive labs (another 350 SAR) and gave me strict instructions: minimum 2,000 kcal daily, focus on easily digestible foods, stop all exercise for one week, follow-up in 5 days.

The weekend was about tiny steps. I bought easy foods with the remaining money: yogurt, bananas, peanut butter, white rice, eggs. Nothing that required 'cooking' because I had no energy for that. Saturday and Sunday I hit about 1,600-1,700 kcal each day - still under target but double my recent intake. No workouts per doctor's orders. Sleep improved slightly (6.5hr average) probably because my body was desperate to heal.

The tremors are still there but slightly less constant. The scale showed 83.1kg by Sunday - I'd regained 0.8kg, probably water and glycogen as my body started getting fuel again. I'm terrified of gaining fat, but I'm more terrified of what the doctor said about 'cardiac complications from prolonged malnutrition.'

Workout adherence: 0/4 sessions (0%). Doctor-mandated rest, but honestly I couldn't have done them anyway. Diet adherence: maybe 60% of target calories, 40% of protein target. Still failing, but failing upward for the first time in two months.

I've agreed to weekly check-ins with my brother and the follow-up appointment Friday. The crisis isn't over - I'm still severely compromised - but I finally accepted I can't do this alone. The 'comfortable numbness' is fading, replaced by fear and something that might be hope. I don't know if I've caused permanent damage. The doctor mentioned possible long-term metabolic effects, bone density concerns, and the need for mental health support.

This week taught me that rock bottom has a basement. But also that asking for help isn't weakness - it's the only thing that saved me from hospitalization.

Week 9 Report - Medical Recovery Phase:

This week was completely different from the nightmare of Week 8. Having my brother's support and the doctor's strict orders gave me structure when I couldn't create it myself. The fear of permanent damage is real now - not abstract anymore.

Monday-Tuesday: Still felt weak but the tremors were less intense. Following the refeeding protocol was hard because my appetite is still suppressed, but I forced myself to eat every 3 hours like the doctor ordered. The 2,000 kcal minimum felt impossible at first. I managed about 1,850 kcal Monday, then pushed to 2,100 Tuesday. No workouts - doctor's orders, and honestly I couldn't have done them anyway.

Wednesday-Thursday: Energy started returning in small waves. I could walk to the corner store without feeling dizzy. Hit 2,200 kcal Wednesday, and Thursday I actually felt hungry for the first time in weeks - managed 2,400 kcal. The meal plan helped because it's structured, though I simplified some recipes due to my beginner cooking skills. Protein shakes became my friend for hitting protein targets without feeling overly full.

Friday: Follow-up appointment. Blood work came back - doctor said I was 'lucky' because electrolytes were low-normal but not critical, liver enzymes slightly elevated but recovering, testosterone low (expected with malnutrition). He was pleased with the 2kg weight gain but warned most is water and glycogen restoration. Cleared me for light walking only, no resistance training yet. Need another week of recovery minimum. This news was both relieving and frustrating.

Weekend: Pushed calories to 2,500-2,600 to accelerate recovery. Sleep improved to almost 7 hours - probably because my body isn't in crisis mode anymore. Took short 15-minute walks both days. My brother checked in Saturday and we talked about what happened. First time I've really opened up about the mental spiral. He's helping me set up the mental health referral appointment.

Physically: Weight climbed to 85.1kg by Sunday. I know it's mostly water, glycogen, and digestive content, but seeing the scale go up doesn't trigger panic like I thought it would - I'm just relieved to not be dying. Muscle mass probably gained minimally (maybe 0.3kg actual tissue), but the rehydration makes measurements unreliable. Still look gaunt but less skeletal. Grip strength slightly better.

Mentally: The fog is lifting. I can focus on tasks for more than 10 minutes now. The dissociation is less constant. But I'm also confronting what I did to myself, which brings waves of shame and fear. The mental health referral can't come soon enough. I'm scared of relapsing into restriction once I feel 'better.'

Adherence: Diet 95% - I hit or exceeded the 2,000 kcal minimum every day, averaging 2,300 kcal (93% of the 2,458 target, but above medical minimum). Protein averaged 155g (84% of target - much better than last week's 39%). Workouts: 0/4 (0%) but medically prohibited, so this was correct adherence to medical orders.

Barriers overcome: Financial stress reduced with brother's help. Medical guidance provided structure. Fear became motivating rather than paralyzing.

Ongoing concerns: Long recovery timeline ahead. Uncertainty about when I can train again. Fear of psychological relapse. Need to address underlying mental health issues that enabled this crisis. Medical bills still a concern but manageable with family support.

This week proved I can recover if I follow the plan. The question is whether I can maintain this when supervision decreases and old patterns try to resurface.

Week 10 started with cautious optimism but reality hit hard. Monday's second medical follow-up brought mixed news - bloodwork improving but doctor still hesitant about exercise clearance. He saw my eagerness and warned me about rushing recovery. That stung because I KNOW he's right, but sitting still feels like going backwards.

The diet plan at 2,454 kcal felt more manageable this week compared to last week's struggle to eat enough. My appetite is genuinely returning, which is both relieving and scary - I'm terrified of overshooting and gaining fat after working so hard before the crisis. Hit around 2,380 kcal average, so 97% adherence. Protein was easier at 178g/day average. The 30 SAR daily budget stretched further now that I'm not buying random snacks out of desperation.

Workouts were the frustration point. Plan called for W25 and W21 sessions 4x/week, but I'm STILL not cleared for resistance training. Did walking only - 25-30 minutes on Mon/Wed/Fri/Sat at moderate pace. It's something, but watching the program slip further away is mentally draining. That's 0/4 actual workout adherence again, though I'm complying with medical orders.

Sleep averaged 6.9 hours, slight improvement. Still waking up anxious about 'wasting time' but the exhaustion isn't as bone-deep anymore. Brother checked in twice this week - once supportive, once clearly frustrated I'm not 'fixed' yet. Told him recovery isn't linear and he backed off.

Mental health intake appointment happened Thursday. Therapist was... intense. Lots of questions about control, body image, self-worth. She used the term 'maladaptive coping' and suddenly everything felt too real. Agreed to weekly sessions but I'm not sure I'm ready to unpack everything. Baby steps.

Physically, I feel stronger than Week 9 but nowhere near normal. Gained another 0.8kg, mostly continued rehydration and digestive normalization. Muscle feels slightly fuller but that's probably just glycogen. The mirror shows someone who looks less skeletal but still depleted. 

The hardest part? Patience. Every day not training feels like muscle wasting away, even though logically I know rest IS the treatment right now. My baseline adherence propensity (0.55) kept trying to sabotage me - wanted to sneak in push-ups or skip meals to 'make up' for forced inactivity. The medical fear and family accountability are the only things keeping me compliant.

Doctor scheduled ANOTHER follow-up for Week 11 with potential training clearance if liver enzymes normalize. Crossing fingers but trying not to hope too hard. At least I'm not in crisis anymore. That's something.

Week 11 complete. This was probably the hardest week mentally since the crisis started. I'm physically feeling better - energy is good, I look less like a skeleton, the shakes are basically gone - but my head is a complete mess. Monday's follow-up was devastating. Doctor said bloodwork is 'improving' but still won't clear me for resistance training. Another week of just walking. I wanted to scream. The rational part of me knows I crashed hard and need time, but the other part is panicking about losing everything I built.

I stuck to the diet plan all seven days, averaged around 2,420 calories which hit the target almost perfectly. Protein was consistent at 180g daily. But eating this much while NOT training feels wrong in my gut. I keep calculating how much fat I'm gaining, running the numbers in my head during meals. My therapist (second session Wednesday) called this 'catastrophizing' and pointed out I'm actually still underweight for my height, but the fear is real. I can see my abs fading and it triggers something.

Walking compliance was 100% - Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday like prescribed, 25-30 minutes each time. But it feels like nothing. I caught myself adding an extra 10 minutes on Saturday and immediately felt guilty, like I was cheating the medical orders. Then felt stupid for feeling guilty about WALKING. My brain is exhausting.

Thursday I almost broke. Found myself in the apartment complex gym at 11pm, just standing there looking at the barbell. Didn't touch it, but I wanted to so badly. Texted my brother instead of lifting - he called immediately and talked me down. He said 'you almost died, idiot, a few more weeks won't kill you but lifting might.' He's right but I hate it.

Sleep averaged 7.1 hours this week, best since before the crisis. Fewer anxiety dreams. Appetite is fully back - actually felt hungry before meals instead of forcing food. That should feel like progress but it scares me too. Therapy is helping me see these thought patterns but not yet changing them.

Weight went up again to 86.3kg. I know intellectually this is good - rehydration, tissue repair, glycogen restoration. But seeing that number climb while sedentary makes my chest tight. Body composition is probably shifting the right direction (more muscle hydration, less severe deficit) but I can't see it, just the scale number.

The positive: my coordination is back to normal, I can focus for longer periods, my skin looks healthy instead of grey, I'm not freezing all the time. These are real improvements. My resting heart rate normalized to low 60s instead of the scary 40s. Bloodwork showed liver enzymes almost normal, testosterone rising but still low. Doctor says if next Monday's labs are clean, I MIGHT get cleared for bodyweight exercises - pushups, air squats, that level. Not the program, but something.

I'm complying because I'm genuinely afraid of ending up back in that place, but the baseline part of me that doesn't stick to plans is fighting hard. Only external accountability is keeping me on track - brother's check-ins, therapy appointments, doctor visits, knowing I have to report honestly. Without that structure I'd have already done something stupid.

Three more days until next medical check. Trying to focus on that potential clearance instead of the frustration. Budget held fine at 30 SAR/day, meal prep is routine now. Physically recovering, mentally struggling, but still moving forward I guess.

Week 12 started with the medical follow-up I've been anxiously waiting for. Monday's bloodwork came back - liver enzymes normalized, testosterone still climbing but not optimal yet. The doctor gave me conditional clearance for bodyweight exercises only, no weights still. I should feel relieved, but honestly I'm terrified. What if I push too hard? What if I don't push hard enough and lose everything I had?

The first bodyweight session (W25 modified) on Monday was humbling and emotional. I could barely do 8 proper push-ups when I used to rep out 30+ easily. My legs shook during bodyweight squats. But I finished it, and my brother was there watching to make sure I didn't go rogue. Tuesday I walked instead of the scheduled W21 because I was genuinely sore and didn't want to risk it.

Wednesday's W25 session went slightly better - 10 push-ups this time. I'm tracking every rep obsessively, which my therapist pointed out Thursday is a control behavior. She's right, but I can't stop. The body image stuff is getting worse. I look in the mirror and see someone soft and undefined, even though rationally I know I'm recovering from near-organ failure and should look exactly like this.

Thursday I was supposed to do W21 but I made an excuse about fatigue and just walked. Honestly, I think I was scared of how weak I'd feel again. Friday I pushed through another W25 - 12 push-ups, small victory. Saturday was supposed to be W21 but I substituted walking again, telling myself I was being 'cautious' but really I was avoiding the discomfort.

The diet adherence stayed strong - 2,510 kcal average, protein on point at 185g daily. But every meal feels like a mental battle. I'm eating maintenance calories while feeling weak and looking soft, and my brain keeps screaming that I'm just getting fat. I know it's irrational. The scale barely moved (86.5kg, +0.2kg), and my therapist says that's perfect. But the distortions are loud.

Sleep improved to 7.3 hours average. My brother checked in 4 times this week, including staying for two workout sessions. I'm compliant on paper - 2 out of 4 prescribed workouts completed as bodyweight modifications, 2 substituted with walking. That's 50% adherence, which given my 0.55 baseline propensity and the psychological warfare I'm experiencing, feels like both a victory and a failure.

The fear is still keeping me somewhat in line, but I can feel my old patterns creeping back - the rationalization, the 'just this once' thinking, the avoidance. Week 13 I need to hit all 4 sessions, even if they're hard. Even if I'm weak. Especially because I'm weak.

Week 13 complete. This week felt like walking a tightrope between physical progress and mental deterioration. I'm stronger - objectively, measurably stronger - but I can't stop catastrophizing about how I look. The mirror feels like an enemy.

Monday's workout was good. W25 bodyweight session, hit 14 push-ups in the first set, up from 12 last week. My brother was there supervising, which helped me push through the discomfort of feeling weak. But afterward, I spent 20 minutes body-checking in the bathroom mirror, pinching at my sides, convinced I'm getting fat during recovery. Rationally, I know 86.7kg is still 10kg above crisis weight. Emotionally, every kilogram feels like failure.

Tuesday I was supposed to do W21 but substituted a 45-minute walk instead. Told myself it was 'active recovery' and 'listening to my body,' but my therapist would call that avoidance. The truth? I was scared of feeling weak again. The walk felt safer, more controllable. I tracked every step obsessively - 6,847 steps exactly.

Wednesday's W25 session I did alone. Mistake. Without accountability, I cut it short after the main circuit, skipping the finisher. Hit 15 push-ups though, which should feel like victory but instead triggered anxiety about whether I'm recovering 'fast enough.' Spent the evening calculating how long until I'm back to pre-crisis strength, spiraling into worst-case scenarios.

Thursday was therapy. Fourth session. We talked about the body-checking, the obsessive tracking, the avoidance patterns. She used the term 'body dysmorphia' directly for the first time. I intellectually understand what she's saying - that my perception is distorted, that the eating disorder cognitions are separate from the physical reality - but I can't *feel* it. The fear feels so real. She suggested we discuss medication options if things don't improve. That scared me more than it should have.

Friday's W21 session I actually completed fully. Brother was there again. 20 bodyweight squats felt easier than two weeks ago. Lunges didn't make me dizzy. Plank hold hit 45 seconds. Physical progress is undeniable, but I felt disconnected from it, like watching someone else's body improve. Ate my full 2,650 calories that day but felt guilty about every bite past 2,400.

Saturday I skipped the workout entirely. Just... couldn't. Woke up, looked in the mirror, felt disgusted, and the thought of exercising felt overwhelming. Went for another walk instead - 8,200 steps, told my brother I was 'being cautious' about overtraining. He didn't buy it but didn't push. I know this is the 0.55 adherence propensity reasserting itself. The medical fear that drove compliance in weeks 9-11 is fading, and my baseline patterns are coming back.

Sunday's W25 was partial. Did the warm-up and main circuit but quit before the finisher. Hit 16 push-ups in the first set - a new post-crisis high - but couldn't celebrate it. Just felt angry that 16 is still pathetic compared to where I was.

Diet adherence remained perfect on paper - 2,641 kcal daily average, 196g protein. Seven days of hitting targets. But the psychological experience of eating is getting worse, not better. I'm eating out of fear (medical consequences) and compliance (therapy homework), not from any healthy relationship with food. Every meal involves mental negotiation. Every snack triggers guilt that I have to logic my way through.

Sleep improved to 7.5 hours average, which is objectively good. But I'm waking up anxious, immediately body-checking before even getting out of bed. The first thought most mornings is dread about what I'll see in the mirror.

Weight crept up to 87.1kg by week's end (+0.6kg). Muscle mass estimate 29.9kg (+0.2kg). Fat percentage holding at 28.4%. The numbers say recovery is progressing appropriately. My brain says I'm losing control, getting fat, failing.

Completed 2.5 out of 4 prescribed workouts (62.5% adherence, slightly above my 0.55 baseline but below the 75-100% I maintained during acute crisis). The trajectory is clear: as physical danger recedes, psychological issues intensify, and adherence declines toward baseline propensity.

Protective factors: therapy engagement, brother's support (probably prevented complete workout abandonment), bloodwork continues improving (testosterone rising per Monday's follow-up), visible strength gains (8→16 push-ups over three weeks). Risk factors: body dysmorphia intensifying, avoidance patterns solidifying, emotional eating compliance weakening, baseline low adherence reasserting, fear-based motivation fading.

I'm physically healthier than I've been in months. Mentally, I feel like I'm sliding backward. The gap between objective progress and subjective experience is widening. My therapist says this is common in eating disorder recovery - the physical healing can outpace the psychological healing, creating cognitive dissonance. Understanding that doesn't make it less terrifying.

Next week needs to address the avoidance directly. Can't keep substituting walks for prescribed workouts. Need to discuss medication options seriously. Need to find motivation beyond medical fear before adherence collapses completely.

Week 14 complete. This felt like watching myself slide backward in slow motion. Started strong Monday with W25—pushed through 17 push-ups, new personal best, brother spotted me—but that victory felt hollow. Like I'm getting stronger while simultaneously falling apart mentally.

Tuesday's W21 cardio session was mechanical. Just going through motions. 28 minutes of intervals while my brain screamed that I'm still too fat, still not doing enough. The mirror at the gym lies—I see 87kg but my mind sees 95kg. Therapist called this 'dysmorphia' but knowing the term doesn't make it stop.

Wednesday I skipped entirely. Told myself I'd go after iftar but just... couldn't. Sat in my room scrolling through fitness transformations on Instagram until 11pm. That comparison trap is poison but I can't stop drinking it. Thursday tried to compensate with W25 again—only managed 14 push-ups, felt like failure despite being above my week-start baseline. 

Friday's W21 was another avoidance walk. 35 minutes of just moving to check a box. Saturday and Sunday—complete collapse. The fear that drove me through the medical crisis weeks is gone, and without it I'm just a guy with 0.55 adherence propensity staring down a program that requires 1.0.

Diet was technically perfect again—2,547 kcal average, 192g protein daily, every meal logged and measured. But I'm white-knuckling it. Every bite feels like swallowing anxiety. I've started cutting my chicken into smaller pieces so it takes longer to eat, giving me more 'control.' That's not normal. I know that's not normal.

Weight up to 87.6kg (+0.5kg). Muscle holding at 30.0kg (+0.1kg). Fat 28.3% (-0.1%). The numbers say I'm recovering perfectly. My brain says I'm getting fat and weak simultaneously. The gap between objective reality and subjective experience is a canyon now.

Therapist wants to start medication next session. I'm scared of it but also scared of where this is heading without intervention. Brother noticed I've been quieter, asked if I'm okay. Lied and said I'm fine. 

Completed 2.5/4 workouts (62.5%). That's above my baseline propensity but feels like failure compared to the 75-80% weeks when panic was driving me. The crisis-motivation is fading and I don't have healthy motivation to replace it with. Just fear of food, fear of mirrors, fear of becoming the person I was at 118kg.

Sleep averaged 7.4 hours but quality is shit. Wake up at 5am with my heart racing, thinking about the day's calories before I'm even conscious. That's not recovery—that's just a different kind of sick.

Physically I'm rebuilding. Psychologically I'm collapsing. And I don't know which one wins.

Week 48 was challenging but manageable. Started at 106.9kg with decent motivation to tackle fat loss. Workouts were tough but completed. Alternating W25 and W21 four times this week pushed me hard as a beginner. Walking up stairs at work became a slow, painful process. The soreness peaked around Day 4-5, making me question if I overdid it, but I pushed through the remaining two workouts anyway, just with even more conservative weights.

Sleep stayed consistent at my usual 6.6 hours. I know I should be getting more for recovery, especially with the new training load, but work deadlines and evening habits kept me up. I felt the fatigue accumulating by mid-week - that groggy, heavy feeling in the afternoon that even coffee couldn't fully fix.

Budget management was key. At 35 SAR per day, I bulk-bought chicken breast (8kg), 5 dozen eggs, and large bags of oats and rice from the wholesale market. This kept costs down but made meals repetitive. Grilled chicken with rice became my default. Breakfast was always scrambled eggs or oats with protein powder. My beginner cooking skills meant I stuck to simple preparations - no fancy seasonings, just salt, pepper, and occasionally some hot sauce for variety.

Hydration was my weak point. I'd start the day with good intentions but by afternoon I'd realize I'd only had one bottle of water. This probably contributed to feeling more fatigued and might have impacted recovery.

The scale showed a small drop by week's end - about 0.8kg down to 106.1kg. Some of that is probably water weight and glycogen depletion from the caloric deficit and new training stimulus. I feel slightly leaner around my midsection, though it's hard to tell definitively after just one week. Muscle mass stayed roughly stable, maybe a tiny increase from the newbie gains phenomenon, but realistically it's too early to see significant changes.

Body fat percentage dropped minimally from 34.2% to about 33.7% - a small win but in the right direction. The combination of mild caloric deficit (actual intake vs expenditure) and resistance training is the right formula, I just need to stay consistent.

Overall, I'd rate this week a moderate success. I proved I can stick to the workout schedule even when sore and tired. Diet adherence needs improvement, particularly with snack timing and hydration. The 55% adherence propensity feels accurate - I'm not perfect, but I'm showing up more often than not. Next week I need to: 1) prep snack containers in advance, 2) set phone reminders to drink water, 3) maybe reduce workout intensity slightly to avoid burnout, and 4) try to get to bed 30 minutes earlier at least 3 nights.

Week 9 was a grind that tested my resolve more than my muscles. Started strong Monday with W25, felt controlled and methodical despite the chronic sleep debt. Tuesday's client emergency shattered my nutrition plan—that late-night shawarma was survival mode, not a choice. Wednesday bounced back beautifully; the 6.2hrs sleep made a real difference and my bench press felt powerful. Thursday I made the smart call to cut W25 short when my legs were screaming, but then sabotaged myself with that midnight date-and-labneh raid while doom-scrolling. Friday's missed W21 was necessary—my body was wrecked from 5.1hrs sleep and I'm learning not to force it. Saturday's meal prep session was clutch, setting up next week's success. Sunday closed strong with W21 at 79%, no heroics but solid execution.

The pattern is clear now: when sleep dips below 5.5hrs, everything falls apart. My adherence propensity of 55% played out exactly—hit 3 of 4 workouts (75%), but nutrition was volatile with that Tuesday spike and Thursday raid. The meal prep investment on Saturday felt like taking control back. Budget crept to 37.1 SAR/day due to emergency takeout and convenience items when exhausted, but that's reality when working 13-hour days.

Weight barely moved (-0.2kg to 104.7kg), which is frustrating but expected given the calorie volatility and water retention from stress. Body composition feels slightly tighter in the mirror despite the scale, maybe from those three solid workouts. The 5.9hrs average sleep is killing my progress—I know it, but client demands aren't changing. Next week I need to protect that 6+ hour threshold at least 4 nights, even if it means saying no to late calls. The meal prep system works; I just need to defend my boundaries better when chaos hits.

Two consecutive weeks of fat loss - this is actually happening.

Workouts: Mon W25 at 82% intensity (felt strong, good start), Tue W21 at 88% (pushed hard), Wed W25 at 76% (fatigue showing from poor Thursday sleep-in-advance), skipped Thu W21 (work crisis), recovered Fri W21 at 79% (grateful I could salvage this). Goblet squats holding at 28kg, focusing on form over progression this week. Back mobility routine only happened 4/7 days - noticed stiffness returning by Friday.

The wins: Budget discipline paying off (35.8 SAR is closest I've been to target), meal prep strategy proving its worth, still maintaining >65% workout adherence despite major Thursday disruption, fat loss continuing for second week. The reality checks: Sleep regression is concerning (6.8hr isn't sustainable), missed mobility routine days correlate with back tightness, one work crisis nearly derailed everything, mental fatigue from poor sleep affected workout quality.

Psychological state: More grounded than last week's high. Last week felt like "I've figured it out!" - this week reminded me this is a process with ups and downs. But here's the thing: even my "down" week was still a win by old standards. 3/4 workouts, budget nearly hit, continuing fat loss, no complete derailments. The systems I've built (meal prep, morning workout slots, phone-away protocol) caught me when I stumbled.

The Thursday pattern is real though - two weeks of data confirms it's my vulnerability point. Need to build even more redundancy around it. Maybe Wednesday night meal prep specifically for Thursday? Or blocking Thursday mornings as non-negotiable in my calendar?

Looking at the two-week trend: 91.8→91.3→90.9kg (-0.9kg total), fat 25.8%→25.5%→25.2% (-0.6% total), muscle stable at 36.5kg. This is sustainable fat loss territory (0.45kg/week average). Not dramatic, but real and maintainable.

Next week focus: Get sleep back to 7+ hours (5/7 nights minimum), complete 4/4 workouts again (prove last week wasn't a fluke), maintain budget discipline (35.8 was so close to 35!), hit mobility routine 6/7 days (back health is non-negotiable), implement Thursday-specific protection strategy. The foundation is solid - now I need to stabilize it.

Week 9 complete. This was a reality check week - hit the adherence ceiling hard. Started strong with 3 workouts in first 4 days, but Friday's work crisis cascaded into weekend disruption. Sleep averaged 6.6hr (down from 6.8hr last week), with two brutal nights under 6hr that tanked recovery. Only completed 3/4 workouts (75% adherence again, matching propensity), missing Saturday's W25 after Friday's 5.1hr sleep disaster. Diet held surprisingly well at 2,791 kcal/day (+6 over target) and 35.2 SAR/day (+0.2 over budget) - meal prep systems continue proving their worth even when life gets chaotic.

Weight: 90.9→90.5kg (-0.4kg, third consecutive week of losses). Body comp shows the grind paying off: muscle maintained at 36.5kg (protein averaging 207g kept this stable), fat 25.2%→24.9% (-0.3%, now -0.9% over three weeks). This is real fat loss, not water fluctuation. The math is working even when execution isn't perfect.

Workout quality was bipolar. Monday's W25 at 86% felt great (7.3hr sleep helped), Tuesday's W21 hit 91% intensity (best in weeks), Wednesday's W25 dropped to 73% as cumulative fatigue hit. Friday's crisis meant 11hr workday plus only 5.1hr sleep, so Saturday's workout was a non-starter - chose recovery over forcing it. Back stiffness returned with vengeance by Thursday, only did mobility 3/7 days.

The concerning pattern: I'm maintaining 75% workout adherence but can't break through to 100% (4/4). Two weeks now of 3/4 completions. Sleep is the obvious culprit - only 2/7 nights over 7hr this week (Mon 7.3hr, Sun 7.6hr). The Thursday-Friday crisis pattern is becoming predictable: work stress → late night → poor sleep → missed workout. Need better crisis protocols.

Bright spots: Didn't stress-eat during Friday's chaos (stayed at 2,805 kcal/36.1 SAR), goblet squats progressed to 30kg on Monday (finally!), water intake solid at 2.7L average. The systems (meal prep, morning workout slots, budget tracking) are keeping the floor high even when the ceiling stays frustratingly out of reach.

Psychological state: frustrated but not defeated. Three weeks of consistent fat loss proves the process works. I'm not failing - I'm succeeding at 75% when my propensity is 65%. But I want that 100% week. The gap between what I'm doing (good) and what I know I'm capable of (great) is annoying. Sleep is clearly the bottleneck - everything else cascades from that.

Next week priorities: (1) 5/7 nights >7hr sleep (non-negotiable, will set hard 22:30 phone-down rule), (2) Friday crisis protocol (pre-log workout as 'optional recovery' to remove decision fatigue), (3) mobility routine 6/7 days (back is screaming for this), (4) attempt 4/4 workouts but with smarter recovery assessment. The three-week fat loss trend is gold - need to protect it while fixing the sleep foundation.

Week 9 complete! Started strong Monday with W33 workout - felt powerful, hit 95% adherence on the session. Squat depth is locked in now, feels natural. Diet was solid at 87% - meal prep Sunday really paid off. Sleep was decent at 7.1 hours, woke up refreshed.

Wednesday hit W29 - this one's always challenging. Completed 89% despite some lingering fatigue in legs from Monday's squats. Sleep dipped to 6.3 hours Tuesday night due to neighbor noise, felt it during the workout. Diet 76% - had to substitute quinoa for rice (store was out), added extra olive oil which bumped calories slightly.

Thursday was my meal prep anchor day again. Spent 90 minutes cooking - chicken breast, brown rice, roasted vegetables, boiled eggs. This rhythm is really working. Diet 81%, sleep recovered to 6.9 hours. Noticed my work pants are looser in the waist.

Friday rest day, diet compliance 79%. Had a social coffee meeting, resisted the pastries but had a cappuccino (not in plan, ~80 kcal). Sleep 6.5 hours - right at that threshold where I feel it the next day.

Saturday crushed W21! 92% workout adherence, felt explosive. The shoulder definition is really showing now - caught myself flexing in the gym mirror. Diet 88%, added an extra banana post-workout for the carbs. Sleep Friday night was rough at 6.1 hours, but adrenaline carried me through.

Sunday recovery day, diet 84%. Took a 30-minute walk in the evening, felt good to move without intensity. Meal prepped again for the week ahead. Sleep caught up at 7.4 hours - body needed it.

Overall: 3/3 workouts completed with high quality. Diet averaged 82.6% (up 3.6% from Week 8!). Budget came in at 312 SAR (44.57/day) - stayed under this time by skipping the shawarma temptation and using more lentils/eggs. The Thursday meal prep is the MVP of my week.

Physical changes: Belt is on the next notch now (total ~2cm waist loss since Week 6). Shoulders have visible striations even at rest. Face definitely leaner - got comments from two colleagues. Scale only down 0.3kg but the mirror tells a different story - clear recomposition happening. Upper body feels fuller, especially chest and shoulders.

Sleep averaged 6.76 hours (down 0.04 from Week 8 but still in range). The 6.5-hour threshold is real - anything below that and I feel it in energy and recovery. Need to protect that Tuesday/Friday sleep better.

DOMS: Moderate Monday-Tuesday from squats, mild Wednesday-Thursday, minimal Friday-Sunday. Recovery is getting faster. No injuries, knee feels solid after last week's minor twinge.

Motivation remains high. The visual changes are incredibly reinforcing. Deadlift went up another 2.5kg Saturday. Squat form is automatic now. I'm starting to feel athletic again, not just 'working out.'

Challenges: Mid-week sleep dips are the main barrier. Work stress was moderate this week (one late meeting). Budget discipline improved - the meal prep system is both cheaper and better for adherence.

Next week: Focus on protecting sleep Tuesday/Friday nights. Maybe try magnesium before bed. Keep the Thursday meal prep anchor. Consider adding a fourth workout day if recovery continues improving, but not rushing it. The recomposition is accelerating - trust the process.

Week 2 (W48) complete and honestly, I'm feeling the cumulative effects now. Started at 63.6kg and managed to drop to 62.8kg, which is encouraging but I know some of this is water weight. The good news is I actually improved my adherence slightly - hit 4 out of 7 days on diet compliance again, but this time I was more mindful about my 'off' days and only added about 100 extra calories instead of 150.

Workouts were TOUGH. I attempted all three this week (W33, W29, W21) but had to modify heavily. W33 (Upper Body) left me sore for three days - I'm talking can't-lift-my-arms-to-wash-my-hair sore. I've learned I absolutely MUST scale these 'Advanced' workouts down to beginner modifications. Did W29 (Core) on Wednesday with reduced reps and it was manageable. By Friday's W21 (Legs), I was still dealing with residual soreness but pushed through with bodyweight-only versions of the exercises.

The 7-hour sleep schedule is my saving grace - I'm religious about it now because I notice if I get less, my hunger signals go haywire and adherence drops. Budget-wise, I'm getting smarter. Spent about 240 SAR this week (staying just under my 245 SAR weekly budget) by buying chicken thighs instead of breasts, using more eggs and lentils for protein, and batch-cooking on Sunday.

The muscle soreness is real though. My upper body is constantly tight, and I'm learning that at 45+ and beginner fitness level, recovery is just as important as the work itself. I'm considering adding a rest day between workouts or doing very light movement on off days. The 147g protein target is challenging on my budget but I'm managing with strategic shopping.

Body composition changes are subtle but there - clothes fit slightly better around the waist, though the scale doesn't show dramatic changes. I think I'm in this for the long haul and need to adjust my expectations. My cooking skills are improving out of necessity - made a decent chicken stir-fry and egg-based meals that hit my macros without breaking the bank.

Biggest barrier remains the workout intensity mismatch. I need beginner-appropriate programming, not scaled-down advanced workouts. But I'm proud I showed up three times this week despite the soreness.

The positive: I maintained my 7 hours of sleep every night, and I can feel my body slowly adapting. My clothes fit slightly better, especially around my waist. I'm learning to listen to my body more - when the DOMS is too intense, I scale back rather than pushing through and risking injury.

The challenge: My adherence propensity of 58% is pretty accurate - I'm hovering right around there. Being 45+ and a beginner means recovery takes longer than I'd like. I need to plan better for those high-stress work days. Maybe prep some compliant snacks in advance?

Looking ahead: I want to get back to that 57% adherence from W48. I'm thinking of doing some meal prep on Sunday evenings to make weekday compliance easier. Also considering lighter workout modifications to manage DOMS better.

The workouts themselves were challenging but doable when I modified them. W29 (Wednesday's leg day) left me hobbling for two days - those squats and lunges really hit hard even at reduced weight. The afternoon energy crashes hit me Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday, making it hard to stay focused at work.

On the positive side, I do feel like I'm building a routine. Three gym sessions completed is better than zero, and even at 50% diet adherence, I'm more conscious of what I'm eating than I was before. The DOMS (muscle soreness) was constant but manageable - actually felt kind of good knowing I was working my muscles.

Biggest barriers this week: budget limitations leading to meal boredom, insufficient sleep affecting energy and willpower, work stress triggering overeating, and general fatigue making it hard to prep meals or stick to the snack schedule. Moving forward, I need to find more budget-friendly variety in meals, work on that sleep schedule, and maybe prep snacks in advance so I don't skip them.

Week 49 was a grind, honestly. Started at 105.6kg and I'm feeling the weight of everything - literally and figuratively. The workouts happened, which is something I'm proud of, but they were HARD. The 6.5 hours of sleep isn't cutting it. I wake up tired, hit an energy wall around 2-3pm every day, and by evening I'm ravenous. Had a couple nights where I broke and ate extra bread or rice just to feel full. Water intake was inconsistent - some days I did okay, others I barely drank anything until dinner.

Budget constraints are real. I'm eating a lot of eggs (cheap protein), rice, frozen vegetables, and chicken when I can afford it. Meal prep is still a challenge with my beginner cooking skills. A few meals were just scrambled eggs and rice because I didn't have energy to cook properly.

Positives: I showed up for all three workouts even when I didn't want to. I can feel my body adapting slightly - the soreness is a bit less severe than previous weeks. I'm learning which exercises I need to modify. The scale moved down a tiny bit, which keeps me motivated.

Struggles: Evening hunger is brutal. Work stress makes it hard to stay consistent. I'm not recovering well with this sleep pattern. My body fat percentage feels stubborn. I know at 45+ and being a beginner, progress will be slow, but it's frustrating. Some days I question if this is worth it, but then I remember why I started - I need to get healthier for the long term.

Hunger was a real issue this week. Three nights I found myself raiding the kitchen around 9 PM, adding extra rice or bread just to feel satisfied. My water intake was inconsistent—hit maybe 1.5L on good days, but two days I barely drank a liter. Afternoon energy crashes were brutal, especially Tuesday and Thursday. I tried pushing through with black coffee, but it only helped so much.

Diet adherence was around 50-55%, I'd estimate. I stuck to the calorie target loosely, but definitely went over on two days with those evening snack attacks. Protein was okay most days thanks to the chicken and eggs, but I know I'm missing out on variety and probably some nutrients. The 30 SAR budget is tight—I can't afford much beyond basics, and the monotony is wearing on me.

On the positive side, I completed all three scheduled workouts without skipping, which feels like a win given how tired I've been. I'm starting to notice small changes—my shirts feel slightly less tight around the midsection, and I think my arms look a bit more defined. The scale hasn't moved dramatically, but I wasn't expecting miracles in one week. I'm down maybe half a kilo, which feels realistic given my partial adherence and the fact that I'm just starting out.

Overall, I'd say this week was a 6/10. I showed up, did the work, but the barriers (sleep, stress, budget, hunger) definitely held me back from being fully consistent. Need to figure out how to manage those evening hunger episodes better—maybe shifting more calories to dinner or having a planned snack. Also need to prioritize sleep somehow, though with my schedule that's easier said than done.
