The same chicken and rice combo is wearing me down mentally. By Wednesday, I was so tired of eating the same thing that I almost ordered takeout, but remembered my 30 SAR budget wouldn't allow it without sacrificing other meals. Thursday was particularly rough - work was chaos, I skipped my planned workout (only managed 2 out of 3 this week), and ended up eating an extra portion of rice late at night because I was starving and couldn't sleep. The 6.5 hours of sleep isn't cutting it for recovery, I can feel it in my joints and energy levels. Friday I tried to get back on track, did my workout, but the afternoon energy crash was brutal. Weekend was mixed - Saturday I meal prepped which helped, but Sunday I had a family gathering and ate more than planned. The scale isn't moving as fast as I'd hoped, which is discouraging. I know I'm only at 52% adherence, but it feels like I'm trying harder than that number suggests. Water intake was poor again, maybe 1.5L most days. My body feels slightly different though - pants are a tiny bit looser, so something is happening. Just wish it was faster and easier.

Week 52 was honestly one of the toughest weeks I've had in a while. Started Monday with decent intentions - got my W33 workout done early morning before work, felt good about that. The workout itself was challenging but manageable, though I'm still feeling like a beginner even after all these weeks. Tuesday and Wednesday the diet held together okay, stuck to my basic meal prep routine though I'm so tired of eating the same chicken and rice combinations. The monotony is really getting to me now.

Thursday was supposed to be my W29 workout day, but work absolutely crushed me. Had a major deadline and stayed late, got home around 8pm completely drained. Skipped the workout and honestly just made myself a quick meal and crashed. Sleep that night was terrible - maybe 5.5 hours - kept waking up thinking about work stuff. Friday I was dragging all day, the afternoon energy dip hit me like a truck. Had 4 cups of coffee just to stay functional. Ended up eating an extra serving at dinner because I was genuinely starving, probably added 300-400 extra calories.

Saturday I managed to get the W21 workout in, moved it from Thursday. It was rough - my body felt heavy and uncooperative. The DOMS from Monday's session had mostly faded but I wasn't feeling strong at all. Diet-wise Saturday was okay until evening when I got hit with serious hunger pangs around 9pm. Ended up having some extra bread with cheese, maybe 250 extra calories. Sleep Saturday night was poor again, around 6 hours but restless.

Sunday was a mixed bag. No workout scheduled which was a relief honestly. But we had an extended family thing in the afternoon - my brother's place. I tried to be mindful but there was a lot of food, traditional dishes, desserts. I didn't go crazy but definitely ate more than my plan, probably 500+ extra calories. The social pressure is real, and honestly after a tough week I didn't have the willpower to be super strict.

Overall completed 2 of 3 workouts again, which seems to be my pattern lately. Diet adherence was maybe 50% - I kept the basic structure most days but had 4 days with extra portions or unplanned eating (Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday). Water intake was poor again, probably averaging 1.4-1.5L. The 30 SAR daily budget is holding but the food boredom is intense. I'm seeing very minimal progress on the scale and it's honestly demotivating. My clothes might fit slightly better but it's hard to tell. The combination of poor sleep (averaged maybe 6.3 hours this week), work stress, and diet fatigue is making everything harder. I know I need to push through but after 52 weeks I'm really feeling the grind.

Starting Week 1 of 2026 feeling exhausted from last year's grind. It's like I'm running on fumes and the scale barely moved despite all that effort. Budget is still tight at 30 SAR/day, which means I'm eating the same bland rotation again. Monday was W33 workout day - got through it but felt heavy and sluggish. The exercises felt harder than they should, probably because I only slept 6 hours last night. Tuesday I skipped the workout (W29 was scheduled) because work dumped an urgent project on my desk and I was at the office until 8pm. Grabbed a shawarma on the way home (over budget, around 25 SAR) because I was too tired to cook. Wednesday I tried to get back on track with the diet - eggs and bread for breakfast, rice and chicken for lunch and dinner. But honestly, the food monotony is killing me. I'm so tired of eating the same things. Thursday was supposed to be rest, but I felt guilty about Tuesday so I did W29 workout in the evening. Mistake - I was already tired and the workout quality was poor. My legs were still sore from Monday. Friday I completely fell off the wagon. Work stress hit again, I had three cups of coffee just to function, and by evening I was starving. Ate an extra large dinner portion plus some biscuits while watching TV. Probably 600-700 kcal over target. Saturday was W21 workout which I actually enjoyed more - felt slightly better energy. But then evening came and I got hit with intense hunger, ended up eating extra rice and chicken, plus some leftover bread. Another 400 kcal over. Sunday was a family gathering at my brother's house - lots of kabsa, sweets, and social pressure to eat. I tried to be moderate but definitely overate by 500+ kcal. Sleep has been terrible all week, averaging maybe 6.2 hours with restless nights Wednesday and Friday. Water intake is poor, maybe 1.3-1.5L per day. I'm feeling discouraged and honestly questioning if this is worth it. A whole year of effort and I'm still over 100kg with barely visible changes. The scale moved down only 0.3kg this week despite doing 3 workouts, which feels like nothing for the effort. My clothes fit about the same. I'm battling constant fatigue, the food is boring, work keeps interfering, and I don't see the point sometimes. Maybe I'm just destined to be this weight. The only positive is I did manage all 3 workouts this week, even if Thursday's was subpar. But the diet adherence was maybe 50% at best - 4 days of excess eating out of 7. I need to figure out how to manage stress eating and evening hunger better, but when I'm exhausted from poor sleep and work pressure, willpower just evaporates.

Week 2 started with some hope but honestly ended in a familiar pattern of frustration. I completed 2 out of 3 scheduled workouts which feels like a step backward from last week's perfect attendance. Monday's W33 workout went okay - not great, still feeling tired but I pushed through. Skipped Thursday's W29 completely because work exploded again with another urgent deadline and I was running on 5.5 hours of sleep. Managed W21 on Saturday morning which felt decent, probably my best session of the week.

Diet was a disaster again. Maybe hit my targets on 2-3 days max. Monday and Tuesday were okay-ish, stuck to the meal plan mostly. Wednesday I was so exhausted I grabbed a chicken shawarma wrap for lunch (wasn't even hungry, just stressed) and then overate at dinner because I felt like I'd already blown it. Thursday was terrible - the work stress plus skipping the workout made me feel like garbage, so I stress-ate through the evening, probably 600-700 kcal over. Friday was passable in the morning but evening hunger hit hard again. Weekend was mixed - Saturday morning good, but Saturday night I was starving after the workout and definitely overate. Sunday started fine but afternoon family visit meant traditional foods and I couldn't resist, probably another 400-500 kcal over.

Sleep is killing me. Averaged maybe 6 hours, with Wednesday and Thursday being particularly brutal (5.5 and 5.8 hours). I'm constantly tired, which makes everything harder - the workouts feel like climbing a mountain, and resisting food when I'm exhausted is nearly impossible. Coffee consumption is up again, hitting 4 cups on the bad days just to function.

The psychological toll is getting heavier. I'm now over a year into this effort and the scale barely moves. Lost maybe 0.2kg this week, which feels like nothing for all the suffering. I look in the mirror and still see the same person. The meals are so monotonous - chicken, rice, vegetables, repeat. I'm mentally exhausted from the constant calculation and restriction. Part of me wonders if this is even worth it anymore. Maybe this is just who I am now.

Budget was tight again. That Wednesday shawarma set me back about 23 SAR and created stress for the rest of the week. Had to skip buying extra vegetables I wanted. Water intake was poor, maybe 1.4L daily average. I know I should drink more but I just forget when I'm stressed or busy.

The missed Thursday workout really bothers me. I was doing so well last week with all three sessions, and now I'm back to skipping. The pattern feels inevitable - work pressure builds, sleep suffers, workout gets sacrificed, then I eat poorly because I feel bad about missing it. It's a cycle I can't seem to break.

I'm trying to stay committed but the motivation is at rock bottom. Every week feels like two steps forward, one step back. Or maybe one step forward, one step back. I don't even know anymore. The worst part is feeling like I'm letting myself down repeatedly. I start each week with intention and end it with disappointment.

Body feels okay physically - some soreness after Monday and Saturday workouts but nothing terrible. It's the mental exhaustion that's overwhelming. I need something to change but I don't know what. Maybe the approach, maybe my expectations, maybe my entire life situation. All I know is this current pattern isn't sustainable and I'm running out of energy to keep trying the same way.

This week was challenging. The meal plan had way too many calories for fat loss - nearly 3000 kcal seems excessive when I'm trying to lose weight. I managed to stick to about half the meals as planned, but often reduced portions or skipped the 4th meal because I felt it was too much food. The workouts were labeled 'Advanced' but I'm a beginner, so I had to modify most exercises significantly. I could only complete about 2 of the 3 planned gym sessions - my body wasn't ready for that intensity. The chicken shawarma and grilled chicken were good, but cooking multiple meals daily with my beginner skills was time-consuming. Sleep remained poor around 6 hours due to work stress. I did see a small drop on the scale, probably from being more active and not eating my usual junk food, even though I wasn't fully adherent to this specific plan.

الأسبوع كان صعباً بصراحة. حاولت الالتزام بالنظام الغذائي والتمارين لكن ظروف العمل وقلة النوم أثرت علي كثير. ألم الظهر رجع لي في منتصف الأسبوع وهذا خلاني أتردد في بعض التمارين. الأكل الحلال مافيه مشكلة لكن أحياناً أنسى أسجل الوجبات أو أفوت وجبة بسبب الانشغال. حاولت أمشي شوي زيادة عن العادة لكن ما كنت منتظم. الميزان ما تغير كثير وهذا محبط شوي، لكن أعرف إني لازم أصبر وأستمر. المدرب داعمني والحمد لله، بس أحس إني محتاج أنظم وقتي أكثر ونومي لازم يتحسن عشان أقدر أكمل بشكل أفضل.

Week 5 of 2026 is in the books. Honestly, it was a grind. Started Monday with good intentions - prepped some simple meals Sunday night (grilled chicken, rice, frozen veggies), but by Tuesday I was already behind. Work got hectic and I skipped breakfast both Tuesday and Thursday, grabbing a shawarma wrap instead of my planned meal around noon. That probably pushed me over on sodium those days. 

Workouts were tough. Managed two full sessions (W33 on Monday evening and W29 on Thursday), but had to bail on Saturday's W21 workout. My lower back started acting up again Wednesday night - that dull ache that tells me I overdid something. I think it was the bent-over rows on Monday, even though I kept the weight light. By Friday I was exhausted from another string of 6-hour sleep nights, so I pushed the third workout to Saturday morning, but woke up stiff and decided rest was smarter than pushing through pain.

The two workouts I did complete felt okay - kept RPE around 6-7 like I'm supposed to, did the bodyweight squats and modified push-ups from W33, then the resistance band work from W29. Sweated a good amount but energy was definitely not peak. Evening timing (around 20:45-21:15) is all I can manage with my schedule, but it's probably affecting my already poor sleep.

Diet adherence was maybe 55-60% this week. Hit my protein target on maybe 3 days - the chicken and some canned tuna helped. But I definitely went over on carbs a couple days (that shawarma wrap, plus I had rice with most dinners). Tracked what I could in my app but I know I'm probably off by 15-20% on portions. The 30 SAR daily budget is tight - spent about 210 SAR for the week on food, which is right at my limit. Had to buy pre-cooked rotisserie chicken twice (18 SAR each) because I didn't have energy to cook.

Step count was all over the place - got 5800 steps on Monday when I walked during lunch, but Tuesday and Wednesday were barely 3000. Averaged maybe 4100 for the week. 

Positive: I didn't completely give up. I showed up for two workouts even when tired. I made some decent food choices when I could. Negative: The back pain is concerning, sleep is still terrible (averaging just over 6 hours), and I feel like I'm treading water rather than making progress. Weight feels about the same, maybe down half a kilo but hard to tell with daily fluctuations. I'm noticing my pants fit slightly better around the waist, so maybe something is happening, but energy and motivation are low. Need to figure out this back issue and somehow get more sleep, or this is going to keep being a struggle.

Week 6 was challenging but I managed to push through better than I expected given my back issues from last week. Started Monday feeling cautious about my lower back, which thankfully felt about 70% recovered. I completed 2 out of 3 planned workouts again - managed W33 on Monday evening and W29 on Thursday, but had to skip W21 on Saturday because I had a family gathering that ran late and I was completely exhausted by the time I got home around 22:30. 

Diet-wise, I'd say I hit around 55% adherence, similar to last week. The calorie target of 3186 felt quite high and honestly I don't think I reached it most days, which might be good for fat loss but I know the plan is designed for a reason. I tracked more carefully this week after realizing my 18% error rate last time. My estimates put me between 2700-3200 kcal most days. I skipped breakfast twice again (Tuesday and Friday) - mornings are just so rushed with work. Hit my protein target on 4 out of 7 days this time, which is an improvement. I've been trying to include more chicken and eggs when I remember.

The sodium is still a problem - I had takeout twice (Wednesday night after a long day, and Sunday lunch with family). Both times I know I went over the 2500mg limit. The shawarma place I go to is just so convenient and within budget, but I can feel the bloating the next day.

Budget was good - spent about 205 SAR for the week, staying under my 210 limit. I'm getting better at finding affordable protein sources at the local market.

Sleep averaged 6.2 hours again, ranging from 5.5 to 7 hours. Wednesday night was particularly bad (5.5 hours) because of work stress, but I managed 7 hours on Saturday which felt amazing. I can definitely tell the difference in my energy and motivation when I get closer to 7 hours.

The workouts I did complete felt manageable at RPE 6-7. My lower back held up well during W33 and W29, though I was very careful with form and took extra rest between sets. Step count averaged around 4200 this week - slightly better than last week's 4100, but still far from ideal. I'm trying to park further from the office entrance to add a few steps.

Motivation is moderate. I can see very minor changes when I look in the mirror - my shirts feel slightly less tight around the waist, which keeps me going. But the fatigue is real, especially mid-week. The 20:45-21:15 evening workout window is working when I can stick to it, though it does cut into my already limited sleep time.

Overall, I feel like I'm maintaining rather than making dramatic progress, but given my starting point and the barriers I'm facing (sleep, back pain, time constraints), I'm trying to be patient with myself. Small consistent steps forward.

This week was challenging but showed incremental progress. I managed to complete all 3 scheduled workouts (Monday W33, Wednesday W29, Saturday W21), which is a personal best for me in recent weeks. The key was planning ahead - I moved Saturday's workout to early afternoon before my family commitment, which helped me avoid the fatigue that derailed me last week.

Diet adherence was around 58%, slightly better than last week's 55%. I tracked more consistently using my phone app, which helped me stay aware of portion sizes. My main wins were: hitting protein targets 5 out of 7 days (up from 4 last week), and only skipping breakfast once (Sunday, slept in after late Saturday night). However, I still struggled with sodium - exceeded limits 3 times this week due to convenience eating on Tuesday (shawarma wrap during work rush), Thursday (family ordered pizza), and Saturday evening (grabbed fast food after workout because I was starving and didn't meal prep).

Calorie intake ranged from 2600-3400 kcal across the week, averaging around 2950 kcal daily - still above my 2400 target but better controlled than previous weeks. The days I meal-prepped (Monday, Wednesday, Friday) were much better for adherence. My budget came in at 198 SAR for the week, which felt good - I'm learning to shop smarter with bulk chicken breast and frozen vegetables.

Sleep remained a struggle at 6.1 hours average (range 5.0-7.0 hrs). Tuesday night was particularly rough (5 hours) due to work stress, and I definitely felt it during Wednesday's workout - my energy was low and I had to reduce weights slightly on the compound movements. The nights I got 6.5-7 hours, I felt noticeably better.

Workout performance: Monday's W33 session felt strong (RPE 6.5), I'm seeing progression on my squat form and managed to add 2.5kg to the bar. Wednesday was tougher due to poor sleep (RPE 7.5), but I pushed through. Saturday's W21 workout was satisfying - completing it felt like a mental victory after skipping it last week. Lower back continues to feel good with no pain flares, which is encouraging.

Step count improved to ~4800 average this week. I started parking further from my office and taking a 10-minute walk during lunch break on 4 days, which added about 1000 steps daily on those days. Small change but it's helping.

I'm noticing my pants feel slightly looser around the waist, and my wife commented that my face looks less puffy. These small wins keep me motivated. The biggest barrier remains evening fatigue and the temptation to skip workouts or grab convenient (unhealthy) food. I'm trying to address this by doing more weekend meal prep, but my cooking skills are still pretty basic - I can handle grilled chicken, rice, and steamed vegetables, but variety is lacking and sometimes I just crave something different.

Overall, I'm cautiously optimistic. The consistency with workouts this week felt like a breakthrough, and if I can maintain this 3x/week pattern while tightening up the diet just a bit more, I think I'll start seeing more noticeable physical changes. Next week's focus: better meal prep variety and protecting my sleep schedule.

Week 8 was a mixed bag - started strong but hit some walls mid-week. Monday's workout felt great, riding the momentum from last week's breakthrough. I actually woke up motivated, which hasn't happened in a while. Tuesday's eating was decent, stuck to the plan mostly. Wednesday was rough - only got 5 hours sleep because of work stress, and I could feel it during the workout. My energy was dragging, and I ended up grabbing a shawarma meal (about 1100 kcal) because I was too tired to prep anything. Thursday I skipped the planned rest day walk because exhaustion caught up. Friday's workout happened but felt like I was moving through mud - RPE was pushing 8 when it should've been 6.5. Weekend was better for sleep (got 7 hours Saturday night!), and Sunday's workout was solid again. The diet adherence dropped back to around 50% - I hit the protein targets 4 out of 7 days instead of 5, and sodium was high again (exceeded 4 times this week). Budget came in at 205 SAR, still under limit but higher than last week. The convenience eating crept back in when sleep got bad. Weight is down slightly which is encouraging, but I can feel the sleep debt affecting everything - recovery, food choices, motivation. The positive: I still hit all 3 workouts even when feeling rough, so that consistency is sticking. The challenge: I need to figure out this sleep thing because it's clearly the linchpin. When I'm tired, everything else falls apart - I eat worse, recovery suffers, and workouts feel harder than they should.

Week 3 in the books, and honestly, it's been a rollercoaster. Started strong on Monday with good intentions after a decent weekend recovery, but the sleep debt hit me hard mid-week again. My protein intake was inconsistent - some days I nailed it, others I barely hit 150g. The sodium is creeping up again because of the restaurant food. I tracked about 3250 calories average, which is way above my 2400 target. The scale shows a small gain, which is frustrating but not surprising given the week I had.

The positive? My clothes are definitely fitting better around the waist. I can button my work pants without that uncomfortable tightness. My wife even commented that my face looks less puffy. These small wins keep me going.

Sleep averaged 6.1 hours again, but the distribution was worse - two nights under 5.5 hours really messed with my recovery and decision-making. I need to prioritize getting to bed earlier, especially before workout days. The cascade effect is real: bad sleep → poor food choices → guilt → stress → worse sleep.

Moving into week 4, I'm setting a specific goal: lights out by 10:30 PM at least 4 nights this week. If I can crack the sleep code, I think the nutrition will follow. Budget was fine at 198 SAR - stayed within limits even with the convenience meals because I balanced with cheaper options other days.
